Local leaders have cautioned politicians against propagating ethnic politics ahead of the August 8 polls. They called on the National Cohesion and Integration Commission to investigate and arrest leaders making inciting statements to get votes. Speaking at Deliverance Church in Kapenguria, the leaders led by Senator John Lonyangapuo urged church leaders to pray for the country and preach peace. &nbsp;Lonyangapuo asked residents to elect development minded leaders and shun politicians making inflammatory statements. Deputy Governor Titus Lotee accused some leaders of propagating lies and campaigning on tribal lines. He has urged leaders to shun statements that might result to violence. ALSO READ: IEBC should leave no room for foul play at August poll